{
    "analysis": "From the previous aggregation results we have global summaries (count and global P95) for many component-KPI series across the entire available time span. Observations: metric groups (e.g., many Redis and Mysql KPIs, IG01 CPU KPIs, Tomcat session metrics) and trace groups (dockerA/dockerB, MG01/IG02 traces) all have data covering the incident window (2021-03-04 18:00 to 18:30 +08). log.error_count for Tomcats and apaches are zero in global P95, and error_logs.csv appears empty for the window. To progress we must follow the workflow: compute global thresholds (we already have P95 per series), then extract the metric points inside the incident window and run anomaly detection (points exceeding the global P95). This will narrow candidate faulty component-KPIs and yield earliest anomaly times to locate faults. Therefore the next atomic step is metric-level anomaly detection restricted to the possible root-cause components during the incident window to produce a compact ranked list of candidate faulty component-KPIs.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv perform the following: 1) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute the global P95 across the full available series (do NOT filter by time for this step). 2) Filter metric.csv to the incident window 2021-03-04 18:00:00+08:00 through 2021-03-04 18:30:00+08:00 and restrict to cmdb_id values from the provided possible root cause components list (apache01, apache02, Tomcat01, Tomcat02, Tomcat03, Tomcat04, MG01, MG02, IG01, IG02, Mysql01, Mysql02, Redis01, Redis02). 3) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) in the window, count points that are anomalies (value > global P95). Also compute for that group: anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (smallest timestamp with value > P95), max_value_in_window, global_p95, and breach_ratio = (max_value_in_window - global_p95)/global_p95 (if global_p95==0 set breach_ratio to None). 4) Return up to top 20 rows sorted by anomaly_count desc (then by breach_ratio desc), showing columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, global_p95, breach_ratio. Keep outputs compact and text-only."
}

{
    "analysis": "We ran metric-level anomaly detection for the incident window and found multiple (cmdb_id, KPI) groups with anomalies (value > global P95). The most severe breaches (highest breach_ratio) are: Redis01 (OSLinux CPU WIO) with breach_ratio ~7.76 at 2021-03-04 18:01+08, IG01 (OSLinux CPU WIO) breach_ratio ~7.44 at 18:00+08, Redis02 (CPUUserTime) breach_ratio ~6.99 at 18:00+08, Mysql01 (CPUWio) breach_ratio ~3.75 at 18:01+08, and several others with breach_ratio >2.0. Since we observe multiple nodes showing strong deviations, we must use traces to decide which faulty component is the true root cause (trace-level anomalies will help find downstream impacted services). According to the diagnostic workflow, next we should analyze traces for these top candidate components to see which trace series show latency or throughput anomalies within the same window, using global trace thresholds computed from full series before filtering.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Perform trace-level anomaly detection within the incident window as follows: 1) From trace.csv compute global P95 and global P5 for each (cmdb_id, trace_name) using the full available series (do NOT filter by time). 2) Filter trace.csv to timestamps between 2021-03-04 18:00:00+08:00 and 2021-03-04 18:30:00+08:00 and restrict to cmdb_id in this candidate set: [\"Redis01\",\"IG01\",\"Redis02\",\"Mysql01\",\"IG02\"]. 3) For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) in the filtered window, count anomalies where value > global_P95 (high latency) and where value < global_P5 (low throughput), and compute: anomaly_count_high (count of value>p95), anomaly_count_low (count of value<p5), earliest_high_timestamp, earliest_low_timestamp, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, global_p95, global_p5, and breach_ratio_high = (max_value_in_window - global_p95)/global_p95 (set to None if global_p95==0). 4) Return up to top 20 rows sorted by (anomaly_count_high + anomaly_count_low) desc, showing columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, anomaly_count_high, earliest_high_timestamp, anomaly_count_low, earliest_low_timestamp, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, global_p95, global_p5, breach_ratio_high. Keep outputs compact and text-only."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed metric- and trace-level anomaly scans for the incident window. Metric analysis found several node-level CPU and I/O-related KPI faults starting at ~18:00–18:01 (notably Redis01 OSLinux-CPU_CPU_CPUWio at 18:01 and IG01 OSLinux-CPU_CPU_CPUWio at 18:00 with very large breach ratios). Trace analysis shows strong high-latency anomalies originating from IG01 and IG02 starting at 18:00 (IG01 trace.self.duration_p95 and several IG01->Tomcat.* duration_p95 and duration_mean series show early anomalies with large breach ratios). According to the diagnosis rules, since IG01 exhibits both severe metric deviations (CPU WIO) and prominent trace-level latency spikes at the start of the incident window, IG01 is a prime root-cause candidate. The CPU WIO metric points to I/O wait (likely high disk I/O usage) rather than pure CPU usage or network problems. However, before finalizing the root cause component, exact occurrence timestamp, and reason, we must confirm that IG01 has consecutive anomalous metric points (a fault sub-series) at 18:00 and corroborate with IG01 trace timestamps and any logs. Therefore we need the raw, bounded metric and trace points for IG01 within the window to identify the first faulty timestamp and check for consecutive anomalies. No log or error_log evidence for IG01 has yet been inspected.",
